{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_lagarde_ver02/data/sn92073203/00332893087/1945091301/0308.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE FOUR\nThe Skyland Post\nPublished Every Thursday By\nSKYLAND PUBLISHING COMPANY\nWest Jefferson, N. C.\nTHURSDAY, SEPT.\nEntered as Second-Class Matter at\nthe Post Office, West Jefferson, N. C.\nED M. ANDERSON Editor-Publisher\nMRS. ED ANDERSON Ass\u2019t. Editor\nJOHN F. REEVES Ass\u2019t. Publisher\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES PER YEAR\nIn Ashe\u2014s2.oo Outside Ashe\u2014s2.so\nThe Post is glad to publish letters, not too\nlong, on matters of general interest. But\nsuch communications must be accompanied\nby the real name of the writer, even when\nthey are to be published under a nom de\nplume.\n\u201cIf the choice were left to me whether to\nhave a free press or a free government, I\nwould choose a free press.\u201d\u2014Thomas Jeffer\nson.\nCarolina\nf MUSS ASSOCIATJQM?)\nAnd National Editorial Association\nImportant Drives\nLike every other American, we are\ngrateful and happy that we no longer have\nto worry about drives on Tokyo. But here\non the homefront, our drives are not over.\nThe cost of victory and reconversion must\nbe met.\nSoon, the United War Fund Drive will\nget underway and after that, the Victory\nWar Loan. If you are called upon to help\nout in one of these drives, remember that it\nis still important that you do your part.\nMillions of men have been wounded and\nthese must be healed; millions returning\nfrom service must be assisted in reestablish\ning themselves in civilian life, and the\nlarge number left in service must still be\nserved.\nJust because the war is over and be\ncause you are probably a little tired of\nworking on drives, you must not quit now.\nWhen you are called upon, not only for a\ncontribution or an investment, but for\nwork, remember, there is still important\nwork to be done. Do not shirk your duty.\noOo\nRationing Boards\nAccording to information released from\nWashington last week, both Ashe and Alle\nghany counties are to be without rationing\nboards in the near future.\nAs long as rationing is necessary, we\nfail to see why the boards in these counties\nshould be done away with. We notice that\nour neighboring counties of Wilkes and\nWatauga are to retain their boards, ac\ncording to the news story released from\nWashington. There seems to be a number\nthat are to be discontinued. And, of course,\nwe are in favor of cutting all wartime agen\ncies that are no longer necessary. We be\nlieve, however, that service of rationing\nboards, particularly where there is only\none to a county, should be continued as\nlong as the rationing program is necessary.\nThe rationing boards in Ashe and Alle\nghany have done an excellent job of serv\ning the people in time of need. And as\nlong as poeple need rationed goods, we be\nlieve a board will still be vital in order\nto see that their needs are supplied without\ntoo much red tape or delay.\noOo\nHealth And Nutrition\nTime and again it has been proven that\nwe often feel the way we do because of\nwhat we eat. And it has furthermore been\nproven that more people are overfed rather\nthan underfed. When we break this down\nwe find most of the overfed individuals are\nfed too much of the wrong kinds of food\nrather than enough of right kinds of food.\nPerhaps the word vitamin has been\noverworked; but at the same time we can\nnot overlook it. There are certain foods\nthat are certainly more essential than oth\ners. And those- rich; in vitamin content\nshould not be overlooked.\nMost of adults, cling to eating habits\nformed in their youth and that is why it is\nimportant to start children out right in\ntheir eating habits. This is the duty of\nparents. Most children like or dislike\nfoods because of the way and the manner\nin which they are served them. If parents\ndo not eat carrots or other vegetables, in\nmany cases the children will form a dislike\nfor them. There is always that element of\nimitation, \u00b0like father or mother,\u201d that has\nits certain influence.\nThis stressing\nhealth and nutrition. Throughout the year\nthe students will hear much about this.\nThey will make health posters, they will\nbe told in many ways the importance of\ndiet as related to physical development and\nhealth. This is a fine thing and notable\nresults should be achieved; but in order\nto put this program across and to help in\nstill its importance in the minds of the\nchildren, the co-operation of the parents\nis needed. They should not only talk the\nprogram, but try to see that it is carried\nout. Mothers, particularly, have a respon\nsibility and an opportunity of doing much\nfor their children in the preparation and\nserving the right kind of food. Meat has\nits place, certainly; but plenty of milk,\neggs, fruits and vegetables of all kinds are\nmuch more essential to the average child.\nOne of the ways of helping to build a bet\nter world in which to live is to help to de\nvelop healthier, happier children. The\nchildren of today are*the citizens of tomor\nrow. We believe a chance for good health\nis the right of every American child.\noOo\nContour Farming\nThe old style of farming in a straight\nrow, up and down the slope results in each\ncultivator mark forming a channel for ero\nsion. That results in water, fertilizer, and\ntop soil being washed off the land. Na\nturally crop yields are reduced.\nThe above explains why the real farm\ners of the country and the manufacturers\nof farm machinery are definitely convinc\ned regarding the wisdom of contour farm\ning. Just because each row, and other til\nlage marks form small catchment areas,\nwater fertilizer, and top soil are held on\nthe land. Again, naturally, crop yields are\nincreased.\nSoil on the move means waste; it re\nsults in erosion and erosion drains off fer\ntility, it gnaws in the sloping land leaving\ngulleys in its wake. In the process of soil\nmovement, valuable plant food is carried\naway. Crop production is reduced.\nThe U. S. Department of Agriculture\nmakes the definite statement that in lowa\ncontoured corn fields produced 23 bushels\nmore corn per acre than adjacent non-con\ntoured fields. In Illinois the Department\nfound that contour farming increased soy\nbeans 6.2 bushels per acre. Contouring\nboosted potato yields 44 bushels per acre\nin New York State. Wheat yields averaged\n4 bushels per acre higher in the southern\nGreat Plains area. Cotton yields aver\naged 29 pounds more per acre on the con\ntour in Texas. This is not a revolutionary\nmovement in farming. It simply represents\nprogress. Any farm can be contoured. The\nbig spot in the recipe by the Department\nof Agriculture is: \u2018\u2018Lay out the contours\naround the slope, and farm on the level.\u201d\nMany farmers in this area are now\npracticing contour farming. Those want\ning more information about this can re\nceive suggestions and planning assistance\nfrom representatives of the New River\nSoil Conservation District.\noOo\nPulpwood Employment\nThe armed forces are expected to re\nlease 7,000,000 men within the year, all of\nwhom will be looking for jobs. A $35,000,-\n000,000 cutback in war manufacturing has\nalready released millions of war workers.\nIt has been predicted that unemployment\nwill reach 5,000,000 in October, that it may\nexceed 8,000,000 before Spring. All this\nhas brought one all-important word into\nthe consciousness of the American people\nReconversion.\nSuccessful reconversion means expand\ning peacetime production to staggering new\nhighs. It means making more baby car\nriages, flatirons, clothing and automobiles\nthan we ever dreamed of making before.\nIt means raising the standards of living of\nall of America, with our citizens consum\ning more goods, and with more money\navailable for that purpose, than ever be\nfore in our history. It means shifting\nAmerica into a brand-new peacetime econ\nomy which can absorb unemployment so\nwell and so swiftly that only a short time\nwill elapse before anyone who wishes may\nwork again.\nShortages in pulpwood during this peri\nod will mean that paper and paperboard\nwill not be available in sufficient quanti\nties to wrap, pack and package the goods\nbeing turned out by American factories.\nReemployment depends on full production;\nfull production can only be accomplished\nif distribution can be maintained at a high\nlevel. This depends in large part on pulp\nwood.\nTHE SKYLAND POST, WEST JEFFERSON, N. C.\nAshe Gas\nBy Stella W. Anderson\nWhat do you like best about\nAshe county? There are so many\nthings one could enumerate that\nit would be impossible to say. Os\ncourse, the people make the coun\nty and next to the people come\nthe scenery, the altitude and, too,\none must think of the food.\nThe writer had an opportunity\nof taking some people to the Black\nBear Inn recently and it goes\nwithout saying they had never\neaten \u201csuch delicious food be\nfore.\u201d\nSpeaking of the beauties of the\ncounty, we have never seen or\nheard of so many picnics before.\nAnd as a matter of fact we know\nof no better form of entertain\nment at this time of the year. The\nBlue Ridge Parkway and parti\ncularly Bluff Park seem to be\nthe choice spots for these. Even\nthe rains fail to daunt many.\nYouth Sets The Stage\nMembers of the Youth Fellow- j\nship of the West Jefferson Meth\nodist Church, presented a play,\n\u201cOld Maids\u2019 Club\u201d the other\nnight, which was unusually good.\nSome of the young men became\nold maids overnight. Among\nthese was Bernard Graybeal, Jr.,\nin effective black and what is\nmore he carried a cat! All of the\ncharacters were good, but Anita\nWeaver proved to be a striking\nexample of how an old maid\u2019s\nchange of heart and attitude\ncould also change her looks.\nMuch of the credit goes to Myrtle\nDean Graybeal, the director.\nAnd Myrtle Dean, who is a mem\nber of the rising Junior Class at\nthe Woman\u2019s College, is also ac\ntive in dramatics there.\nSinging For Fun\nThere is nothing like getting\ntogether with group singing for i\nreal enjoyment. At the conclu\nsion of the very successful meet\ning of the American Legion and\nAuxiliary ast week, a number of\nthe group really outdid them\nselves. John Littlewood, of Hel\nton, made up no little part of the\nfun. And, of course, there were\nNorman Hege, Ira T. Johnston, A.\nB. Hurt and Commander L. B.;\nTyson in addition to some femin-\nine voices that really chimed in.!\nOne of the factors making the;\nsinging a success was Jim Story i\nat the piano, who was in his usual\ngood form.\nTime And Change!\nAmong the people heard from\nat the meeting was Upton Blev-;\nins. And Upton, who has seem\nservice in three wars, pointed out;\nthe fact that when he was in the;\nnavy 40 years ago, there were no\ni radios, no submarines and no air-\nplanes used in service! Imagine]\nthe changes that have taken place.,\nBecause of his age, Upton was\nnot admitted to the regular I\nbranches of service, but through I\nhis knowledge and skill, was ad-\n,mitted to the Merchant Marines.\n\u201cI did not have an opportunity of\nshooting at the Japs, but I did\nhelp to transport ammunition to\nlour boys and they in turn helped\nito defeat them,\u201d he said. Few\npeople in this county have seen\nI service covering such a long peri\nled of time.\nIn The Mail Bag\nJ. A. Philips, of Kirkwood, Pa.,\nsends in his renewal to this paper\nand writes that he \u201cdoes not want\nto miss a single copy.\u201d He also\ni registers a complaint about the\nslowness of service. We can\u2019t\nblame him for that and hope that\nUncle Sam will soon be doing\nbetter now that the war is over.\nRobert Morphis, former popu\nlar basketball coach, writes from\n[Lynchburg that he receives the\npaper and is much interested in\nthe \u201cPostwar\" objectives by this\npaper and would like to see them\ncarried out\u201d\nAn Elongated Egg\nThere are egges and eggs. This\nyear we have had some unusually\nbig ones, but the strangest one of\nall which is an elongated affair,\nwas brought in this week by\nAmbrose Hopkins. It is around\n3 inches long and not more that}\none-half inch in thickness.\nA. Black, of West Jefferson,\nbrought in a squash that really\nwould squash most people if they\ntried to handle it. Both the egg\nand squash are on display in the\nwindow of this paper.\nCatch forest fires when they\nare young and treat them rough,\nsay Extension foresters of State\nCollege.\nASHE COUNTY MAY\nLOSE RATION BOARD\n(Continued from Page 1)\nNo information as to where ap\nplications in Ashe will be handled\nhas been released.- It is believed\nthey would have to go through\nthe Charlotte office.\nNo notification as to the dis\ncontinuance date has been receiv\ned by members of the board here.\nL. P. Colvard, who has effective\nly served as chairman for some\ntime, pointed out that as long as\nit was necessary to serve the pub\nlic the board was most willing\nand agreeable. \u201cThe discontinu\nance of the board and the office\nwould mean a delay in serving the\npublic on rationed items. We\nfeel that the people of this county\nare entitled to service without\nany unnecessary delay,\u201d Chair\nman Colvard said.\nA number of merchants and\nother individuals have expressed\nthe desire that the office and\nboard be continued as long as the\nprogram is necessary.\n\u201cIf boards are to be maintained\nelsewhere, we certainly need one\n(in this county, considering the\nlarge area and the number of peo\nple served,\u201d one individual de\nclared yesterday.\n\u201cThe people of this county are\nas much entitled to service in\nconnection with rationed goods\nas those elsewhere,\u201d a merchant\nsaid.\nSQUIRREL SEASON TO\nOPEN SEPTEMBER 15\n(Continued from Page One)\nson for other game in this sec\ntion, including quail, would open\non Thanksgiving Day, November\n22.\nAll hunters are asked to be\nparticularly careful about fires I\nthis year. Licenses may be se\ncured from the game warden,\nclerk of court and at some of the\nhardware stores, as usual, it was\nannounced. The delay in getting\nthe licenses has been due to pa\nper and labor scarcity, N. C. Game\nCommissioner John D. Findlay,\nsaid.\nSCHOOLS EXPECT TO\nBEGIN LUNCH PROGRAM\n(Continued from Page 1)\nproved and returned here this\nweek.\nSchools that have already sent\nin applications include West Jef\nferson, Jefferson, Lansing, River\nview, Nathan\u2019s Creek, Fleetwood,\nIdlewild, Healing Springs, Vir-\nginia Carolina, Warrensville,\nTrout, Helton, Duncan, Rock\nCreek and Baldwin.\nMr. Duncan said that other ap\nplications would probably go in\na little later. Last year, Ashe\ncounty led North Carolina in the\nnumber of approved lunchrooms\n.per school population.\nANNUAL FEEDER CALF\nSALE HERE SEPT. 26\n(Continued from Page One)\ninterested in calves to attend, as\nthey can see how the calves are\ngraded.\nNo cross breeds or scrub calves\n\u2018should be entered in this sale, it\nwas stated.\nW. J. FIRE DEPT.\nBUYS A TOWN LOT\n(Continued from Page 1)\nmembers of the town council,\nI were appointed to investigate\nI plans, materials and costs for the\nproposed building and report la\nter.\nANNOUNCE SCHEDULE\nFOR COUNTY CLUBS\ni\ni Monday, Sept. 17, West Jeffer-]\nson 4-H club will meet at the\nschool at 10:30 a. m. All club\nj members are urged to bring their j\n'record books to the club meet-1\ning. j\nTuesday. Sept. 18, Rock Creek.\n4-H club will meet at the school!\nat ten a. m.\nTuesday, Sept. 18, Chestnut\nHill H. D. club will meet at 2:30 i\np. m. at the home of Mrs. Wayne\nGore.\nWednesday, Sept. 19, Elkland\n4-H club will meet at the school\nat 1:00 o\u2019clock.\nWednesday Sept. 19, Baldwin\nH. D. club will meet at the home\nof Mrs. Worth Gentry at 2:30 p.\nm.\nThursday, Sept. 20, Silas Creek\nH. D. club will meet at Silas\n\u2019Creek school at 3:00 o\u2019clock.\nFriday, Sept. 21, Nathan\u2019s\nCreek H. D. club will meet at the\nhome of Mrs. D. M. Bare at 2:30\np. m.\nThe topic for the H. D. club\ni meetings during the month of\nSeptember, is \u201cKnow Your Fab\nrics.\u201d\nBIRTH ANNOUNCED\nMr. and Mrs. Robert J. Ashby,\nof Warrensville, have announced\nthe birth of a daughter, Virginia\nDianne, Saturday, September 8;\nweight, six and three-fourths\npounds.\n1\nMesdames Parkers\nEntertain Group\nMrs. Muncey Parker and Mrs.\nT. E. Parker were joint hostesses,\nat the home of the former, to\nmembers of the Woman\u2019s Society\nof Christian Service of the West\nJefferson Methodist Church, on\nWednesday afternoon, Sept. 4.\nMrs. C. R. Eller hed charge of\nthe program. The scripture lesson\nwas read by Mrs. Levern John\nson, and Mrs. Sharpe Shoemaker,\nMrs. Bernard Graybeal and Mrs.\nEarl Graybeal spoke on \u201cHealth\nAround The World.\u201d Mrs. T. E.\nParker concluded the program\nwith prayer.\nA short business session was\nconducted by the president, Mrs.\nSharpe Shoemaker.\nThe hostesses served a delicious\ncourse of refreshments during the\npleasant social hour which follow\ned the program.\nRiverview School\nWe, at Riverview, are proud\nthat ours is one of the few high\nschools in the county that has\na graduating class this year.\nThis class, although there are\nonly six members, is a very prom\nising one. At present, it is plan\nning a school newspaper to be\ncalled the Wildcat, which will be\nthe first we have ever had. The\npaper will be published monthly.\nJack Graybeal is the .editor and\nthe paper is under the supervision\nof Mrs. Thomas Morton.\nMorris Lewis, formerly of this\nschool, has been in a Japanese\nconcentration camp since his cap\nture in the Philippines nearly\nfour years ago. Since his intern\nment his family has heard from\nhim only twice. They have been\nexpecting news of him since V-J\nDay.\nMiss Pearl Graybeal, who grad\nuated here last year, is now a stu-\nWaiting for a NEW\nGOODYEAR\nYes, Sir, he learned about tires the hard way. Like\nmany other motorists, he experimented, played-the\nfield found nothing satisfied him like a Good\nyear. That's why he's even willing to wait, if neces\nsary, for a new Goodyear a tire you can always\ncount on for extra, long, safe service. See us as\nsoon as you \"see'' a certificate.\n<Sf ff W/ Ixi Al OBPR\nill W /Vi\nI O BUYI I\nl Fi sr IS 20 I\nTUBES, 4.00x16 w _ _\nIT. J.\nM WEST JEFFERSON, N. C.\nTHURSDAY, SEPT. 13, 1945\nBOY SCOUTS ENJOY\nBANQUET TUESDAY\nThe local Boy Scout troop\nthoroughly enjoyed a banquet at\nI the community building, here, on\nI Tuesday evening. Mrs. S. W.\n\u25a0Diggs and Mrs. Dewey Sells had\n'charge of the meal, which was\none of the most bountiful ever\ngiven here. Approximately twen-\nty scouts enjoyed the feast.\nScouter Levern Johnson, who\nhas long been connected with the\nScouting activities of the county,\nmade an impressive talk to those\npresent. Following Mr. Johnson\u2019s\nitalk, Mr. Jim Story, chairman of\nAshe county camping and activi\nties committee, made a few re\nmarks. Other guests included\nAssistant Scoutmaster Harvey\nj Payne, Dewey Sells, and Scout\nmaster E. W. Powers, who presid\ned at the banquet.\nDRAFT CLASSIFICATION\nCHANGES ARE MADE\nMrs. Louis J. Yelanjian, chief\nclerk of the local draft board, an\nnounced this week that because of\na new classification regulation,\nall men between the ages of 26\nand 37 would be reclassified and\nplaced in 4-A.\nYOUNCE TO HOLD\nSERVICE SEPT. 22\nThe Rev. Ray Younce will de\nliver the sermon at the church\nservice to be held September 22,\nat three o\u2019clock at the Laurel\n(Knob Baptist church, it was an\nnounced.\ndent nurse at Grace Hospital in\nMorganton. jk\nJoe Gwyn Price, H. A. 2-C, son w\nof Mr. and Mrs. G. B. Price, is now\nhome on leave. Joe Gwyn is a\ngraduate of this school and has\nbeen in the navy over a year. At\npresent, he is stationed at Norfolk,\nVa.","height":"27117","width":"19989"}}
